@node features "Features"

                                   Features

-Like all my Workbench games, the game window can be resized (up to
 a maximum of 640 x 400 pixels), and the game is redisplayed according to
 the new window size.

-You can move its window where you want on the Workbench screen, and
 of course behind or in front of other windows (this also applies to the
 'About' window).

-The game uses as little of the computer's ressources as possible, so you
 can run other applications, games, etc. at the same time.

-Tri_it works on all Amigas with Workbench 2.0 or higher (Although it may
 run with an earlier Workbench).

-It can be started from CLI or Workbench.

-When first run, it's window size is generated according to the Workbench
 screen size.

-If the window is too small to display the game board, it will
 automatically resize itself to a usable size.

@endnode

@node installit "Installation"

                           Tri_it Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place Tri_it where you want on
your system (hard drive or floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc.). No other files
or libraries are needed.

@endnode

@node play "How to play"

                           How to play Tri_it?

  You play by clicking on the triangular shapes located between the
coloured tiles. This will make a triangular rotation (clockwise)
between the 3 surrounding tiles like this:

       A            C            B
             ->           ->            etc.
    C  *  B      B  *  A      A  *  C

(where A,B and C are the tiles and '*' is the shape where you click.)

BUT!

  Sometimes, when you click, the tile located under MAY move along
with the 3 others, so instead of a 3 tile rotation, 4 tiles will
rotate, as shown here:

       A            D            C

    D  *  B  ->  C  *  A  ->  B  *  D   etc.

       C            B            A

  If you click on the lowermost tiles, you would think that as there
are no lower tiles, only a normal 3-tile rotation would take place...

Think again!

  When there are no tiles under the lowermost tiles, the UPPERMOST
tile act as a 'lower tile' and may move, and the tile at right will
take its place at the uppermost position... in other words, it will 
make the same 4-tile rotation previously explained.


  On the bottom of the game window, there are 3 buttons:

 -@{b}New Game@{ub}:                     To restart the game.

 -@{b}Mini Triangle...Big Triangle@{ub}: To choose between the 4 game sizes.

 -@{b}About...@{ub}:                     Displays the informations about the game.

  There is also a pull-down menu containing the following items:

 -@{b}New Game@{ub}: Restarts the game.

 -@{b}About@{ub}:    Displays the informations about the game.

 -@{b}Quit@{ub}:     Quits the game.

@endnode

